In article <bbosenCIEt17.9yE@netcom.com>, Bob Bosen <bbosen@netcom.com> wrote:
>barryh@pro-cynosure.clark.net (Barry Herman) writes:
>
>I think I'll trundle on down to Radio Shack and see if my local distributor
>has these. Sounds promising...  I'll letcha know. Now about that
>challenge/response algorithm you suggested: anybody have any views
>about cracking it other than brute-force?

You mean r = dec( hex( c xor p ) xor p ) ?

Yes.  The above is equivalent to dec( (hex(c) xor ( hex(p) xor dec(p) ) ).
Note that the last part containing the password is CONSTANT, so we have
r = dec( hex(c) xor something).  Given that decimal-to-hex conversion can
be handled adequately fast by even a modest DX2/66, not to mention the
high-powered TS/1000, it boils down to just r=(c xor something).  Given
one (r,c) pair the cypher is cracked.
